Grep Command

The grep command is a powerful text-search utility in Unix-like operating systems used for searching text using patterns. 
The name "grep" stands for "Global Regular Expression Print."
It searches through files or input provided to it and prints lines that match a given pattern.

Basic syntax
grep [options] pattern [file...]

i: ignore case
Matches patterns regardless of case.
grep -i "pattern" file.txt

v:Invert match
Shows lines that do not match the pattern.
grep -v "pattern" file.txt

-l: List filenames
Displays only the names of files containing the pattern.
grep -l "pattern" *.txt

-n: Line number
Shows line numbers with output lines.
grep -n "pattern" file.txt

-o: only matching
Displays only the matched parts of a line.
grep -o "pattern" file.txt

-E:Extended regular expressions
Allows the use of extended regex features
grep -E "pattern1|pattern2" file.txt





